1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,560
Fighting against the mafia is right, we all agree on that.

2
00:00:03,560 --> 00:00:08,660
But, what if it were also one of the most powerful economic development strategies we have?

3
00:00:08,660 --> 00:00:12,980
And yes, today we look at some data and try to understand what really happens

4
00:00:12,980 --> 00:00:15,660
when the state decides to intervene heavily.

5
00:00:15,660 --> 00:00:19,280
Okay, so the question we're asking is exactly this.

6
00:00:19,280 --> 00:00:23,440
For a long time the answers have been, well, a bit vague, right?

7
00:00:23,440 --> 00:00:26,400
Based on feelings, on "they say that..."

8
00:00:26,400 --> 00:00:28,820
But now things have changed.

9
00:00:28,820 --> 00:00:34,780
There is brand-new research by Di Fenzio and Saggio that finally gives us numbers, real data,

10
00:00:34,780 --> 00:00:38,359
taken directly from the world of Italian businesses and workers.

11
00:00:38,359 --> 00:00:41,400
Let's start with a fact that we unfortunately know well.

12
00:00:41,400 --> 00:00:44,540
Where the mafia arrives, the economy suffocates.

13
00:00:44,540 --> 00:00:46,340
It's as if there's no air.

14
00:00:46,340 --> 00:00:49,620
Companies that want to work honestly get crushed,

15
00:00:49,620 --> 00:00:52,780
competition no longer exists, and it's all a farce.

16
00:00:52,780 --> 00:00:55,380
And those who would want to invest, run away.

17
00:00:55,400 --> 00:00:59,100
This, in short, is the economic damage of crime.

18
00:00:59,100 --> 00:01:02,960
A real handbrake pulled on the economy of a territory.

19
00:01:02,960 --> 00:01:07,079
But, be careful, the state is not just watching.

20
00:01:07,079 --> 00:01:12,879
It has a powerful tool, perhaps one of the most incisive that exists at an institutional level

21
00:01:12,879 --> 00:01:14,719
to fight this problem.

22
00:01:14,719 --> 00:01:17,920
And now let's see exactly what it is.

23
00:01:17,920 --> 00:01:23,359
We are talking about the dissolution of city councils due to mafia infiltration.

24
00:01:23,400 --> 00:01:28,200
It sounds like a complicated name, but the idea is simple and, I would say, brutal.

25
00:01:28,200 --> 00:01:33,400
When it's discovered that local politics and crime are, let's say, a bit too friendly,

26
00:01:33,400 --> 00:01:35,859
the central government wipes the slate clean.

27
00:01:35,859 --> 00:01:38,859
Mayor gone, council gone, everyone gone.

28
00:01:38,859 --> 00:01:42,099
And in their place, external commissioners arrive.

29
00:01:42,099 --> 00:01:43,539
The goal is only one.

30
00:01:43,539 --> 00:01:48,640
To cleanly cut those sick ties and restart the municipal machine on legal foundations.

31
00:01:48,640 --> 00:01:49,739
And let's be clear.

32
00:01:49,739 --> 00:01:52,180
It's not something done lightly.

33
00:01:52,200 --> 00:01:54,880
There is a very, very precise procedure.

34
00:01:54,880 --> 00:01:56,980
Precisely to avoid any abuse.

35
00:01:56,980 --> 00:01:58,020
It works like this.

36
00:01:58,020 --> 00:02:00,520
First, the prefect conducts an investigation.

37
00:02:00,520 --> 00:02:06,360
If they find something wrong, second, the government in Rome dissolves the council and sends in commissioners.

38
00:02:06,360 --> 00:02:13,760
Third, these commissioners govern for a period, usually a couple of years, and then, only then, do people vote again.

39
00:02:13,760 --> 00:02:15,960
And here we come to the central point.

40
00:02:15,960 --> 00:02:21,319
The million-dollar question: does this thing work, does it have a real effect?

41
00:02:21,359 --> 00:02:28,780
Well, the numbers we are about to see speak for themselves and are the clearest answer ever given.

42
00:02:28,780 --> 00:02:30,359
Let's start with the first piece of data.

43
00:02:30,359 --> 00:02:38,859
Nine years after one of these dissolutions, the number of active companies in that municipality has grown by an average of 9.4%.

44
00:02:38,859 --> 00:02:43,659
Think about it, it means the air is breathable again for those who want to do business.

45
00:02:43,659 --> 00:02:46,620
And more business, obviously, means more work.

46
00:02:46,620 --> 00:02:50,180
Look here, employment in the private sector.

47
00:02:50,240 --> 00:02:53,500
A jump of 16.9%.

48
00:02:53,500 --> 00:02:59,319
This isn't a small adjustment, it's a real boom, people finding jobs.

49
00:02:59,319 --> 00:03:04,260
Okay, but someone might say, maybe it's just the black market economy emerging.

50
00:03:04,260 --> 00:03:08,480
Right; in fact, there is data that helps us dispel this doubt.

51
00:03:08,480 --> 00:03:17,740
Prices of industrial properties—warehouses, offices—increase by 15%, and these are transactions that are hard to hide.

52
00:03:17,740 --> 00:03:21,400
So, yes, the growth is real and solid.

53
00:03:21,400 --> 00:03:24,879
There is a fundamental detail, though: when does this growth arrive?

54
00:03:24,879 --> 00:03:26,480
Well, not immediately.

55
00:03:26,480 --> 00:03:32,860
At first, you see a small improvement, but the real turning point, the acceleration, arrives after the third year.

56
00:03:32,860 --> 00:03:33,900
And it's no coincidence, right?

57
00:03:33,900 --> 00:03:38,160
It's exactly when the commissioners leave and people vote for a new administration.

58
00:03:38,160 --> 00:03:42,680
The real major results are then seen in the long term, after almost a decade.

59
00:03:42,680 --> 00:03:45,060
Fine, the numbers are impressive.

60
00:03:45,060 --> 00:03:47,200
But now we have to understand why?

61
00:03:47,340 --> 00:03:48,540
What is the mechanism?

62
00:03:48,540 --> 00:03:52,000
What is it that triggers such a strong economic recovery?

63
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:55,600
Well, there are essentially two hypotheses.

64
00:03:55,600 --> 00:03:57,100
Hypothesis number one.

65
00:03:57,100 --> 00:04:00,100
The commissioners sent from Rome are super-bureaucrats.

66
00:04:00,100 --> 00:04:02,940
Much better and more efficient than local politicians.

67
00:04:02,940 --> 00:04:04,500
Hypothesis number two.

68
00:04:04,500 --> 00:04:10,700
The real reason is that by weakening the mafia, a healthy economy is finally liberated and can start running again.

69
00:04:10,700 --> 00:04:15,300
Let's analyze the first hypothesis, the one about the better commissioners.

70
00:04:15,400 --> 00:04:23,300
If that were the case, we should see, I don't know, more money arriving from Rome or significantly better management of local finances.

71
00:04:23,300 --> 00:04:26,100
And yet no, the data doesn't confirm it.

72
00:04:26,100 --> 00:04:28,100
But the smoking gun is something else.

73
00:04:28,100 --> 00:04:32,100
When a municipality is dissolved for other reasons, unrelated to the mafia,

74
00:04:32,100 --> 00:04:35,100
there is no trace of these crazy economic effects.

75
00:04:35,100 --> 00:04:39,100
So, no, it's not just a matter of good administration.

76
00:04:39,100 --> 00:04:42,400
And so, by exclusion, we are left with the second hypothesis.

77
00:04:42,500 --> 00:04:46,500
Which is what the research confirms without a shadow of a doubt.

78
00:04:46,500 --> 00:04:48,500
The authors' words are clear.

79
00:04:48,500 --> 00:04:52,700
These interventions work because they strike at the mafia's power.

80
00:04:52,700 --> 00:04:57,100
And this, in turn, does something fundamental: it rebuilds trust.

81
00:04:57,100 --> 00:05:00,100
Trust in institutions, trust in the market.

82
00:05:00,100 --> 00:05:03,800
The proof that trust is changing can be seen right at the polls.

83
00:05:03,800 --> 00:05:07,100
After the receivership, people vote differently.

84
00:05:07,200 --> 00:05:10,900
Younger people are elected, with a higher level of education,

85
00:05:10,900 --> 00:05:13,600
and, a very interesting fact, more women.

86
00:05:13,600 --> 00:05:17,400
The usual suspects, professional politicians, drop drastically,

87
00:05:17,400 --> 00:05:20,800
as do those with too many ties to the business world.

88
00:05:20,800 --> 00:05:24,600
It's as if the electorate says "enough, we want a fresh start."

89
00:05:24,600 --> 00:05:26,200
Let's go even deeper.

90
00:05:26,200 --> 00:05:28,200
Where does this growth come from?

91
00:05:28,200 --> 00:05:30,200
Well, it's not distributed randomly.

92
00:05:30,200 --> 00:05:33,000
The explosion of new companies happens almost entirely there.

93
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:35,800
In sectors that have always been the ATM for the mafia:

94
00:05:35,800 --> 00:05:37,800
construction, waste management;

95
00:05:37,800 --> 00:05:40,800
in these fields, the growth is almost 20%,

96
00:05:40,800 --> 00:05:43,300
in other sectors, practically zero.

97
00:05:43,300 --> 00:05:45,100
This tells us something very clear.

98
00:05:45,100 --> 00:05:49,300
The monopolies that crime had imposed by force are being broken.

99
00:05:49,300 --> 00:05:53,400
And if we look at individual companies, the story becomes even clearer.

100
00:05:53,400 --> 00:05:57,000
The companies that were previously friends with the corrupt administration,

101
00:05:57,000 --> 00:05:59,800
those that always won the contracts, what happens next?

102
00:05:59,800 --> 00:06:02,699
They collapse, they lose work, they lose value,

103
00:06:02,699 --> 00:06:05,000
and who grows? Everyone else.

104
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:08,899
Those not connected, those that were previously kept out of the system.

105
00:06:08,899 --> 00:06:10,899
They are the engine of the recovery.

106
00:06:10,899 --> 00:06:14,399
And now, the definitive proof, the smoking gun if you will:

107
00:06:14,399 --> 00:06:17,699
what happens in those municipalities where, after two years of commissioners,

108
00:06:17,699 --> 00:06:20,100
people vote back in the same people as before?

109
00:06:20,100 --> 00:06:23,100
Simple: there is no economic growth.

110
00:06:23,100 --> 00:06:24,100
Zero.

111
00:06:24,100 --> 00:06:26,399
This is the key point of the whole story.

112
00:06:26,399 --> 00:06:30,000
The state's intervention works only if it brings about a real political change;

113
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:32,399
otherwise, it was all useless.

114
00:06:32,399 --> 00:06:34,100
Okay, let's sum it up.

115
00:06:34,200 --> 00:06:37,000
What do we take away from all this analysis?

116
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:39,000
What is the gist of it?

117
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:42,200
The message, in my opinion, is very powerful.

118
00:06:42,200 --> 00:06:45,200
Fighting the mafia when it infiltrates politics

119
00:06:45,200 --> 00:06:48,700
is not just a matter of legality, of justice.

120
00:06:48,700 --> 00:06:49,600
No.

121
00:06:49,600 --> 00:06:53,800
It is one of the most effective economic development policies that exist.

122
00:06:53,800 --> 00:06:56,400
It means unlocking the potential of a territory.

123
00:06:56,400 --> 00:06:58,900
Giving birth to companies, creating real work,

124
00:06:58,900 --> 00:07:01,100
and giving a future to entire communities.

125
00:07:01,100 --> 00:07:03,600
And we close with a question, a provocation

126
00:07:03,600 --> 00:07:06,100
left open by the researchers themselves.

127
00:07:06,100 --> 00:07:09,300
If this policy is so harmful to the mafia's business,

128
00:07:09,300 --> 00:07:12,700
why don't we see the bombs and the violence of the 90s anymore?

129
00:07:12,700 --> 00:07:15,900
Maybe they understood that a head-on collision with the state

130
00:07:15,900 --> 00:07:17,300
ultimately doesn't pay off,

131
00:07:17,300 --> 00:07:19,900
that it's better to blend in, to change their skin.

132
00:07:19,900 --> 00:07:22,000
A question that helps us understand how the fight

133
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:23,600
against organized crime

134
00:07:23,600 --> 00:07:26,100
is a chess game that never ends

135
00:07:26,100 --> 00:07:29,600
and that we must always be ready to understand the next move.

